<paragraph id="8BB7368AD87DFFF23CB4FB9D31B9FF3F" blockId="40.[151,1058,1062,1113]" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">D i a g n o s i s: The two black spots on each elytron, amidst an otherwise yellow elytral color, will distinguish the members of this species from congeners.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD87DFFF23CB4FBD330E0FEE0" blockId="40.[151,1059,1129,1415]" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 6.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD87DFFF23F5CFBD331EBFF18" box="[895,980,1129,1151]" captionStart="Figs 318-321" captionStartId="107.[151,191,1519,1541]" captionTargetBox="[156,1063,202,1502]" captionTargetId="figure@107.[153,1063,192,1502]" captionTargetPageId="107" captionText="Figs 318-321: Habitus; (318) Ampleris ituituba; (319) A. jatai (320) Cregya arima; (321) C. biguttula." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746820" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746820/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">Fig. 321</figureCitation>
. Color: Yellow, except antennal capitulum, tibiae, and tarsi black, and each elytron with two black spots, one at humeral angle, the other behind elytral middle. Head: Antenna (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD87DFFF23FDAFB19328EFFB1" captionStart="Figs 61-91" captionStartId="73.[151,191,1343,1365]" captionTargetBox="[151,1033,198,1310]" captionTargetId="figure@73.[151,1059,198,1328]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="Figs 61-91: Antennae; (61) Madoniella muralla; (62) M. nota; (63) M. acicula; (64) M. aspera; (65) M. baja; (66) M. delta; (67) Amboakis bermejo; (68) Pujoliclerus variolus; (69) Megatrachys irrasis; (70) Cregya arima; (71) Nelsopelonium aspikelum; (72) Cregya vicosa; (73) Pujoliclerus abditus; (74) P. dexus; (75) Cregya triguttula; (76) Pyticeroides brevitubulus; (77) Pujoliclerus lasiosus; (78) Cregya biguttula; (79) Sirpa acara; (80) Parapelonides naranjo; (81) Cregya livida; (82) Amboakis collucoatis; (83) Ampleris jatai; (84) Megaphloeus yasuni; (85) Pelonium implacide, male; (86) Epiphloeus prolixicornus; (87) Pelonium implacide, female; (88) Epiphloeus mantillerii; (89) Amboakis mitaraka; (90) Ellipotoma makrosa; (91) Cregya maura." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746752" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746752/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres shorter towards capitulum, capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 long triangular, antennomere 10 oblong; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye slightly narrower than frons (EW/FW 30/35). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD87DFFF23F73FB413195FE77" box="[848,938,1275,1297]" captionStart="Figs 163-170" captionStartId="79.[151,191,1521,1543]" captionTargetBox="[183,1039,199,1493]" captionTargetId="figure@79.[151,1059,199,1508]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="Figs 163-170: Pronota; (163) Artoadenus atrafinus; (164) Cregya triguttula; (165) C. biguttula; (166) Perilypus schusteri (167) Platynoptera potaro; (168) Pelonium erudiatum; (169) Parapelonides aodontus; (170) Isoparis cassidilis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746764" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746764/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">Fig. 165</figureCitation>
) transverse (PW/PL 100/90), disc finely punctate, lateral tubercle well developed; elytra sculptured with small asetiferous punctures distributed throughout elytral disc, punctures less abundant in elytral distal 1/3 
<superScript id="7C7D9BC2D87DFFF23D9EFAF533F5FE3B" attach="left" box="[445,458,1359,1373]" fontSize="6" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">rd</superScript>
(EL/EW 280/70). Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform, slightly emarginated in posterior margin; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD87DFFF23EA0FACB30E0FEE0" box="[643,735,1393,1415]" captionStart="Figs 237-242" captionStartId="89.[151,191,1264,1286]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,198,1249]" captionTargetId="figure@89.[153,1061,198,1249]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="Figs 237-242: Aedeagi; (237) Cregya arima; (238) C. biguttula; (239) C. vicosa; (240) Eurycaulis anaxeis; (241) Pelonium tayrona; (242) P. implacide." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746784/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">Fig. 238.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD87DFFF23CB4FA2D30D6FECA" blockId="40.[151,745,1430,1452]" box="[151,745,1430,1452]" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">D i s t r i b u t i o n: ThisspeciesisknownfromBrazil.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD87DFFF23CB4FA06337CFD6A" blockId="40.[151,1058,1467,1548]" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">
E t y m o l o g y: The trivial name, 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D87DFFF23E0BFA0130BBFEB6" box="[552,644,1467,1488]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">biguttula</emphasis>
, is a Latin compound name that stems from the prefix 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D87DFFF23D1FFA633367FE88" box="[316,344,1497,1518]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">bi-</emphasis>
(= two) and 
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D87DFFF23DC0FA633028FE88" box="[483,535,1497,1518]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="999">gutta</emphasis>
(= spot); with reference to the two black spots on each elytral disc.
</paragraph>
